1122900856028979203.text: TODAY at 2:25pm ET: High school & college students will ask @AstroHague & @Astro_Christina questions about working & living on the @space_station. This downlink is part of the “Future of Space” #NASASTEM event. Watch live on NASA TV! http://www.nasa.gov/nasatv pic.twitter.com/58FKSCHkAN

1122923619678552064.text: LIVE NOW: The Future of Space broadcast with our leadership and college students from around the country! Tune in to see if your #AskNASA questions are answered. Learn about our careers & find your place in space:https://twitter.com/i/broadcasts/1OdKrvdapelKX …

1121149161192210432.text: Our very own Kristen John (@Jacobs_Science) is the lead of the Hermes facility, an experimental microgravity research facility that will study asteroid regolith. Hermes will launch to @Space_Station next week! Read the @NASA Feature article to learn more:  https://go.nasa.gov/2UxraOZ pic.twitter.com/wadta14RQf

1119646911022161921.text: You know what they say… teamwork makes the dream work! Expedition 61 members and a trainer celebrate at the conclusion of their emergency training inside a space station mockup this week. The crew will join @Astro_Christina, already aboard the station, on her extended mission.pic.twitter.com/Vsaegw3zRY

1121050497375510533.text: On April 25, the public is invited to interact with NASA’s Driven To Explore mobile exhibit at @UTAerospace from 9 am-2 pm CT & join @Astro_Stephanie Wilson as she shares her experience in space during a 10 am CT presentation! #DSAustin2019 https://www.engr.utexas.edu/events/destination-station-international-space-station-day-at-ut-austin …pic.twitter.com/OAvsR9sURx

1121432453443477504.text: To kick off the celebration of the 50th anniversary of @NASA Apollo 10, Snoopy visited @NASA_Johnson Mission Control this morning and waved hello to @NASA_Astronauts up on the International Space Station (@Space_Station). #AstronautSnoopypic.twitter.com/GFGFvx2FMN

1123286565340557312.text:
5 years ago today, the HD Earth Viewing experiment on station began. Now, the stream has been viewed 300 million+ times, giving people a chance to see live views of Earth from space, a view only a few people will ever get to experience in person.

Watch: https://eol.jsc.nasa.gov/ESRS/HDEV/ pic.twitter.com/FzrtOhPWMt

1121424978166124546.text: .@NASA is now targeting July 2 for Orion’s Ascent Abort-2 test flight from Cape Canaveral Air Force Station in Florida. This date provides additional time for work on the launch abort system and takes into account Eastern Range availability.pic.twitter.com/K9Q47J6V3A

1119269424031256576.text: The U.S. #Cygnus space freighter delivered new science today that will challenge future scientists. Also, @Astro_Christina will stay in space until February 2020 and new astronauts @Astro_Jessica and @AstroDrewMorgan are now due to launch to the station.pic.twitter.com/zelaf19bLK

1121507183043203072.text: Snoopy is returning to the moon aboard @NASA_Orion spacecraft and @NASA_SLS rocket that will take future astronauts to deep space and usher in a new era of space exploration.pic.twitter.com/K4W68T1t50

1119291692941828098.text: This morning, flight controllers in Mission Control Houston monitored the @NorthropGrumman S.S. Roger Chaffee Cygnus vehicle as it was captured by @AstroAnnimal before robotics controllers used the Canadarm2 to berth it with the @space_station. https://blogs.nasa.gov/spacestation/2019/04/19/cygnus-cargo-craft-attached-to-station-until-july/ …pic.twitter.com/hkHPV6eNmE

1119322271938695168.text: This week on “Houston, We Have a Podcast,” the voices of those who saved a piece of American spaceflight history tell the tale of reviving obsolete audio equipment vital to digitizing the voice recordings of the Apollo 11 flight controllers in Houston. https://www.nasa.gov/johnson/HWHAP/heroes-behind-the-heroes …pic.twitter.com/4wVmOY1gKC

1120764274572500992.text: Part of the @space_station’s mission is to prepare for voyages beyond low-Earth orbit, which includes learning how to feed future explorers. To that end, astronauts have learned how to grow foods in space. Do you know which of these foods has not (yet) been grown on the station?pic.twitter.com/ZH4D55ca0K

1121517407233769481.text: Today, employees enjoyed an Apollo 10 Lessons & Legacies panel including Apollo 10 commander Thomas Stafford and more NASA leaders. They also met @Snoopy! NASA has shared a proud association with Charles M. Schulz & Snoopy since Apollo missions began in the 1960s.pic.twitter.com/EFA0ma2yK7

1121852079751016449.text: In part 2 of this special edition of our podcast, John Hansen & Greg Wiseman take the first crack at repairing the only machine capable of playing back the voice recordings of Apollo 11 flight controllers, and soon realize they'll need some help… https://www.nasa.gov/johnson/HWHAP/the-heroes-behind-the-heroes-part-2 …pic.twitter.com/MlowGEXEx0

1121431400425693184.text: The crew aboard the @space_station received a special call this morning from @Snoopy & the Schulz family in Mission Control! As we celebrate the 50th anniversary of Apollo 10, we’re working with Peanuts to share STEM curriculum for students. More: https://www.nasa.gov/feature/nasa-and-peanuts-worldwide-to-collaborate-on-deep-space-learning-activities …pic.twitter.com/p6P5YsLYXn

1121489073250734081.text: 50 years ago, Apollo 10 astronauts described their upcoming flight to reporters. Astronauts aboard the Lunar Module would descend to about 50,000 feet above the Moon’s surface & photograph Apollo 11’s landing site in the Sea of Tranquility. https://www.nasa.gov/feature/50-years-ago-apollo-10-a-great-amount-of-team-work …pic.twitter.com/NlD6nfipmy

1123300995822309378.text: The @Space_Station is designed to provide life support for its human crew members so they can complete their mission of research and exploration. Do you know the name of the chemical process that is harnessed to generate oxygen for the crew members to breathe?pic.twitter.com/CIvEPM6mCn

1118929561415299072.text: 50 years ago, Apollo 10 astronauts discussed their upcoming mission, describing the flight as "essentially a dress rehearsal for the Moon landing." The crew participated in simulations of various mission phases using flight simulators at @NASAKennedy. https://www.nasa.gov/feature/50-years-ago-apollo-10-to-sort-out-the-unknowns …pic.twitter.com/dDMjsuHfj4
